S, and Academic Achievement\\n'\n","             'US School Districts (SEDA 6.0 + NCES F-33, 2018-19)',\n","             fontsize=13, pad=15)\n","\n","plt.tight_layout()\n","plt.savefig('heatmap.png', dpi=150, bbox_inches='tight')\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"id":"jhn9-lCXTtk_","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1776040668521,"user_tz":240,"elapsed":1203,"user":{"displayName":"Ishra Naznin","userId":"08772314118732184252"}},"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":807},"outputId":"0896c2b2-8f83-4721-c809-e7e023d8eaf1"},"execution_count":22,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 1000x800 with 2 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["• PerpupilExp vs PerPupilSupport = +.93 have the highest correlation, this makes sense as both are measures of different spending on students.\n","\n","• Log_MedianIncome vs SSE_Composite = +0.88 Very strong positive correlation. Shows how much household income impacts educational outcome.\n","\n","• SSE_Composite vs Pct_FreeReducedLunch = -0.84 very strong negative correlation. If we consider this a measure of poveryty, it only reinforces the correlation we previously saw with Log_MedianIncome\n","\n","• SES_Composite vs Achievement = 0.77 — confirms the above from the positive direction. Variation is possibly due to differences in methodology that might cause a student to preform well on one and not the other.\n","\n","• PerPupilExp vs Achievement = only 0.17 — funding alone has a weak direct relationship with achievement.\n","\n","• PerPupilCashflow vs PerPupilNonInst = -0.44 PerPupilCashflow has no correlation with any other item. It makes sense as non-instructional spending is usually cut as a means to save money.\n","\n","• LocalRevPP vs Achievement = 0.40 — but local revenue (property taxes) correlates much more strongly than total spending. This is the prof's exact point about neighborhood wealth masquerading as a funding effect.\n"